result.execSummary:
The defendant Donovan O Morris was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Probation Review Hearing in Branch 24

Defendant Donovan O Morris in court with attorney Mark Allan Dluzak.  Defendant Donovan O Morris in custody.  Charles Kreger appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Parties have reached resolution. State will read in charges not issued for sentencing.

AS TO COUNT 1:
Pursuant to plea negotiations, on motion of the State, Court ordered Count 1 DISMISSED BUT READ IN.

AS TO COUNT 2:
Defendant changes plea(s) to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to plea, advised of Constitutional Rights and the maximum penalties. Defendant further advised that if not a US citizen, deportation is possible. Court found that the defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived rights.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights form, Addendum, and Elements received and filed. Parties stipulate to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea(s).  Court found defendant GUILTY and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  

 Court vacates Final Pretrial and Jury Trial dates.  Probation Review Hearing scheduled for October 28, 2016 at 01:30 pm.
